        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Diet of this species has not been studied, but the cryptic colouration and apparent sluggish habits suggest it is an ambush predator of invertebrates.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3510",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Species-specific details unknown, but all clinids are livebearers, males copulating with females and fertilizing the eggs internally with their intromittent organs. Juveniles develop inside the females’ ovaries and in most species the live young are born in spring, have a short planktonic life then settle on the bottom. Young juveniles with distinctive body shape and characteristic white, lateral spot.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3511",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
